reviewText: Partial clips in stunning quality are very frustrating to watch. The Hollies clip is from The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour. All songs are edited and incomplete. Graham Nash and Michelle Phillips are decent as hosts, but this is one DVD you will not want to watch more than once. Too bad.
summary: The Hollies were never on The Ed Sullivan Show

reviewText: I have heard much of the same before. Many of these groups had strarted after Buddy Holly. It's like it just exploded into existence. The Beatles gave a lot of credit to him. The Rock and Roll revolution actually began with him, and then the music died. The whole thing just started with them is the impression that one comes away with.  The Beatles themselves mentioned him a lot. All that was needed was to say something like this "After the death of Buddy Holly,a new sound hit the airways". His name didn't come up even once. They hinted at him but that is all.

reviewText: I love the commentary by Michelle Phillips (formerly of the Mama's and Papa's) and the other guy too.  It would have been nice to get a DV of just the performances too.  I wish they had something like that for sale.  All in all, very informative.  I'm shocked at how dumb we all looked back then.  But the music is burned into our brains - those of us about 50 anyway.
summary: The 16 outtakes are great and so is the commentary!

reviewText: This is a really good collection of some of the best rock n roll artists from the 1960s and 70s.  My personal favorite performances on the DVD are The Rolling Stones' "Time Is On My Side," Bob Dylan's "I Don't Believe You," and The Mamas & The Papas "Monday, Monday."  It was a nice suprise to see they included a few performances like James Brown's "Please, Please, Please" which are a little outside the genre but still classic songs.  Definitely recommend!
summary: Great Collection of Classic Rock n Roll

reviewText: Really great! Awesome memorable performances like The Beatles' first US performance on The Ed Sullivan Show, The Rolling Stones, The Beach Boys, The Mamas & The Papas, and many other great artists. Quality is really good. I truly enjoyed it. If you like classic rock, you'll definitely like this DVD. It has great videos from the Ed Sullivan show. Indeed, one of the best, if not the best variety show America's ever had.
summary: Ed Sullivan + classic rock = perfect combo!

reviewText: This is a great set!  Not only is it loaded with some of the best songs by the most prolific artists of the period, but the interviews that go along with them really give thoughtful insight.  My favorite performances were Dylan's "I Don't Believe You", The Stones "Satisfaction", and The Beatles "I Want To Hold Your Hand."  I found this highly entertaining and recommend to any fans of the 60s music scene.

reviewText: If you are looking for some of the best known rock acts of the 60s than this is the DVD.  The collection really captures the music of the decade.  One of my favorite things about the DVD, were the interviews with Michelle Phillips and David Crosby.  Both talked very candidly about their expereinces with their bands and playing on shows like Sullivan.  This is a really great collection for the price
